### Cross-Practice Analysis: Value Proposition Against Traditional Insurance

All five practices share a unified critique of traditional insurance and present DPC as the solution:

**The Deductible Trap Problem**: Traditional insurance with \$7,500â€“\$16,000 deductibles means patients pay full price for primary care despite carrying insurance. DPC solves this with flat, inclusive fees.

**Time Scarcity Problem**: Traditional practices allocate 10â€“15 minutes per appointment due to insurance billing overhead and patient volume metrics. DPC practices offer 45â€“60 minute appointments because they eliminate insurance administration and cap patient panels.[^3][^4]

**Relationship Deficit Problem**: Traditional insurance creates adversarial dynamics (patient vs. insurance company) and incentivizes provider efficiency over listening. DPC practices explicitly position physician-patient relationships as foundational to care quality.[^4][^6]

**Billing Complexity Problem**: Traditional insurance generates surprise bills, denied claims, and complex patient responsibility calculations. All DPC practices emphasize transparent, predictable pricing with no hidden fees.[^5][^3]

**HSA Tax Advantage (New in 2026)**: With the January 1, 2026 legislative change, DPC membership fees (up to \$150/month individual, \$300/month family) can now be paid with pre-tax HSA funds. Only Exponential Health currently markets this advantage, creating a competitive gap for other practices to exploit.[^1][^2]

### HSA/Health Savings Account Compatibility: Critical 2026 Development

**Federal Legislation Impact**: The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (H.R. 1), signed July 4, 2025, explicitly makes Direct Primary Care Service Arrangements (DPCSAs) eligible for HSA funding beginning January 1, 2026. Previously, IRS regulations classified DPC membership fees as health insurance premiums (not HSA-eligible). Section 71308 of the new law reverses this classification, treating qualified DPC arrangements as primary care services rather than insurance.[^1][^2]

**Monthly Fee Limits for HSA Eligibility**: \$150 for individuals; \$300 for families (indexed for inflation). Fees above these thresholds may still be paid with HSA funds but will not trigger HSA contribution eligibility (i.e., you can use accumulated HSA balance to pay fees, but exceeding limits won't preserve your ability to contribute new pre-tax dollars).[^2][^1]

**Qualifying Criteria**: A DPCSA must provide primary care services delivered by qualified practitioners (physicians in family medicine, internal medicine, geriatrics, pediatrics; nurse practitioners; physician assistants; clinical nurse specialists).[^2]

**Marketing Gap**: As of January 2026, only Exponential Health explicitly advertises HSA/FSA compatibility on its website. This represents a significant competitive opportunity for Plum Health, DPCWM, Dr. Klaes, and Red Cedar to update marketing materials and claim HSA eligibilityâ€”a major value proposition for self-employed professionals, gig workers, and small business owners who can now fund primary care with pre-tax dollars.[^5]

### Michigan Market Context: Why DPC Is Gaining Traction in 2026

The timing of this DPC analysis coincides with a healthcare affordability crisis in Michigan. The expiration of federal enhanced premium tax credits on December 31, 2025, resulted in 25,000â€“40,000 fewer Michiganders enrolling in ACA marketplace plans for 2026 compared to 2025. Unsubsidized bronze and silver plan premiums increased 100â€“300% overnight for middle-class Michiganders earning \$40,000â€“\$130,000. Simultaneously, four major insurers (Molina, HAP CareSource, University of Michigan Health Plan, Meridian) are exiting or scaling back Michigan's ACA marketplace, affecting over 200,000 enrollees.[^9][^10][^11][^12]

In this context, DPC practices position themselves as a viable escape route for professionals facing:

- Unaffordable traditional insurance (\$400â€“\$1,000+/month premiums with \$7,500â€“\$16,000 deductibles)
- Carrier exits and forced plan switching
- Loss of established physician relationships
- Subsidy cliff shock for those earning above 400% federal poverty level

The pairing of DPC (\$75â€“\$85/month) with either a high-deductible health plan + HSA or a health-sharing ministry creates a significantly cheaper, more transparent healthcare strategy than traditional comprehensive insurance for many Michiganders.
